explanation: OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - The macro/inline used to obtain 'impl' must be inspected to determine if the read/assignment has side effects (e.g. additional state changes) so removal would change behaviour; needed to decide if that operation is dead. OS_impl_condvar_table - The table/object being indexed by the macro; required to see if the access changes global state or has nontrivial side effects. OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t - Definition (including types of 'mut' and 'cv') is required to know what the code is doing with those fields (passing to pthread APIs or cleanup handler) and whether those operations have externally observable effects. OS_object_token_t - The token type and any dereference semantics (operator* on token) must be known to determine if reading *token has side effects or is purely a simple lookup. OS_Posix_CondVarReleaseMutex - The cleanup handler registered by pthread_cleanup_push; its semantics (what it does to the mutex) determine whether the push/pop pairing affects program behaviour (especially on thread cancellation), so removing the registration could change observed behaviour. pthread_cleanup_push - The macro/implementation that registers cleanup handlers; needed to determine whether its presence has observable runtime effect beyond registration and thus whether it is removable. pthread_cleanup_pop - The macro/implementation that unregisters and optionally executes the cleanup handler; its semantics (pop with false) are central to whether the push/pop pair is effective or dead. pthread_cond_wait - Its behaviour (it is a cancellation point and re-acquires the mutex on cancellation) is central to why the cleanup handler is registered; must be considered to decide if the push/pop are necessary and therefore not dead. OS_ERROR and OS_SUCCESS - The return constants used by the function; required to see whether the return path and status check produce externally observable differences if removed/changed. OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - (Appears in static call graph and may be what OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET expands to) Needed to inspect that implementation for side effects and to confirm whether the token-to-index lookup is a pure read or has other effects. Each of the above symbols is needed to determine whether any executed operation in OS_CondVarWait_Impl has observable side effects (including in cancellation scenarios) such that removing it would change program behaviour (i.e., to rule out or identify dead code).
